PLAGUE, BUBONIC- KAZAKHSTAN (02)
********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
Date: Tue, 03 Aug 1999 13:43:59 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Itar-Tass 03, Aug, 1999 (edited)
See Also
Plague, bubonic - Kazakhstan (Aktyubinsk) 990713103033
Plague, bubonic - Kazakhstan (Aktyubinsk) (02) 990717111432
Plague, bubonic - Kazakhstan 990802230845
Three people, living in the Mangistauskaya Region, Western Kazakhstan,
contracted bubonic plague: a 13-year teenager, his mother and grandmother.
The patients are now at the hospital in the village of Beineu, situated 250
kilometers from the regional administrative center Aktau.
The patients are now stable, although the teenager was in a critical
condition for several hours. Specialists of the local anti-plague center
established the herdsman's family contracted the disease while cutting up
the carcass of a camel: only these animals can fall ill with this disease.
A quarantine was put in placed at that locality. As many as 89 people
contacted the patients. Seven of them were hospitalized and are under
medical observation. They are mostly medics who inspected the patients for
the first time.
Epidemiologists from the republican epidemiological center now work in the
locality. The regional administration appropriated 200,000 tenges (about
1,500 U.S. dollars) for medicines. Measures were taken to localize the
plague seat.
The Mangistauskaya Region is regarded as a higher risk zone for contracting
plague, although the last case of plague was registered in the region 24
years ago. This is the third case of contracting plague in Kazakhstan this
year.
The Aktyubinsk and Kyzylorda regions registered one man each who fell ill
with plague in June.
